with EKS, EKS Workshop is instrumental and super useful. However, there is no way to know the traffic, user-base and metrics on the use of this workshop to get idea on the scale and impact. It would be great to capture aggregated and granular data like # of views, traffic by labs to get some meaningful insights on the use of this workshop. \r\n\r\nAlso, it may be helpful to add a quick notification feature that can alert / notify registered viewers of any future updates / new releases / additions to the workshop. The command "eksctl upgrade nodegroup --name=nodegroup --cluster=eksworkshop-eksctl --kubernetes-version=1.21" in "UPGRADE MANAGED NODE GROUP" section of the  https://www.eksworkshop.com/intermediate/320_eks_upgrades/ should either be "eksctl upgrade nodegroup --name=nodegroup --cluster=eksworkshop-eksctl --kubernetes-version=1.20" or update lab to add / highlight the instruction to set the next version based on current K8 version in the cluster.  \r\n\r\nThis is a trivial bug and something that can be easily troubleshot by looking at events in cloud formation output. 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Security group for pod EKS lab https://www.eksworkshop.com/beginner/115_sg-per-pod/40_sg_policy/ fails to apply security group policy to pod because of groupIds tag in ~/environment/sg-per-pod/sg-policy.yaml missing POD_SG id. To fix it, go to AWS management console, and grab secutiy group id for security group name "POD_SG" inside EC2/Security Groups, and add it under groupdIds tag in the sg-policy-yaml file. 

Rerun following commands:

kubectl -n sg-per-pod apply -f ~/environment/sg-per-pod/sg-policy.yaml

kubectl -n sg-per-pod describe securitygrouppolicy', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eks-workshop/issues/1326/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eks-workshop/issues/1326/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '**"Windows containers on EKS" lab in EKS workshop is broke because of following issues :** 1. "Windows Nodes" section of the lab referencing unsupported version of windows AMI. 2. Format for powershell command param in the YAML doesn't account for escape characters, hence will fail in parsing in executing the steps under "Deploy an application" section of the lab. 3. the URL for docker image in the yaml pointing to an old image in registry and hence fail in creating Windows Pod Below are the steps to fix the lab: **Steps to follow to fix issue # 1 above :** a. Refer AMI release calendar and list of supported AMIs at https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eks/latest/userguide/eks-optimized-windows-ami.html , and identify the AMI family based on your region and version of Kubernetes in your env. b. To point to appropriate AMI family, update "amiFamily" tag in windows_nodes.yaml created as part of steps under "Windows Nodes" section. For e.g. for us-east-1 and K8 version is 1.19.x, the appropriate amiFamily per current supported matrix is WindowsServer2019CoreContainer. c. Rerun the following command to creating the node group : eksctl create nodegroup -f ~/environment/windows/windows_nodes.yaml d. continue with the lab until you hit issue # 2 above. **Steps to follow to fix issue # 2 and # 3 above :** a. Replace the value passed to command param of powershell.exe in windows_server_iis.yaml file with the following: "Add-WindowsFeature Web-Server; Invoke-WebRequest -UseBasicParsing -Uri 'https://dotnetbinaries.blob.core.windows.net/servicemonitor/2.0.1.6/ServiceMonitor.exe' -OutFile 'C:\\ServiceMonitor.exe'; echo '

Hello EKS!!!

' > C:\\inetpub\\wwwroot\\default.html; C:\\ServiceMonitor.exe 'w3svc';" Note - that value should have an escape char for backslash such that it is C:\\ and not C:\ b. Replace the image url to point to correct docker image based on the AMI family. For e.g. if amiFamily is WindowsServer2019CoreContainer, the image tag should be mcr.microsoft.com/windows/servercore:ltsc2019 c. Re-run following command to apply the changes: kubectl apply -f ~/environment/windows/windows_server_iis.yaml d. continue with rest of steps from the lab.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eks-workshop/issues/1322/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eks-workshop/issues/1322/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}
